story:
A long time ago, I learned the difference between being friendly and being a true friend. I've always prided myself on being  a kind and caring person to everyone I meet; I can be helpful toward an old woman crossing the street, or a stranger at the grocey store, but that doesn't make me their friend in any real lasting way. In fact, in the grand scheme of things, it's easy to carry someone's bags or hand them a cereal box from the shelf they can't reach. When I met Augusto, I discovered that real friendsip is sometimes reserved only for the truly hardworking among us.

Augusto and I started chatting online almost 10 years ago, and even though we've never lived within 1000 miles of each other, we hit it off instantly - there was a rare, honest ease to or conversations. But with such naked honesty between us over the years, I came to discover the darker corners of my new friend's heart. We started spending many long nights talking on the phone, and he would often dissolve into tears as he examined the falures and struggles that plagued his daily life. I was always as compassionate as could be, but even as I took pride in being there for him, so too did I begin to suffer my own troubles. I turned down dates and social activities just to talk to my distantfriend on the phone. I lost my focus at work and struggled with the time I had to invest as his sole confidant. Being a true friend, I discovered, ment being generous with my time and energy. I've had more than my fair share of great experiences with him,and I still take pride in the ways I've helped him over the years as we became the best of friends. It has been an education, though, in what it means to be a real friend to someone.

story: One day while I was at the park a middle-aged man approached me and began talking. He told me I looked honest, and that he needed a favor from someone. According to him, his fair mother, who had been caring for him while he had been out of work, had herself taken ill. As hardworking as she was, he said, it was inevitabe that one day her health would suffer. As it would be, her generous nature had its own unfair reward: she had used up all her money to care for her son, the very man who was talking to me now, and in her feeble state had no means to pay the bills. Back o his feet after a painful bout of shingles, he had found employment and saved for such an event. However, pressed for time, he could not make it to the post office to mail the bills, many of which were final notices. Emboldened by this man's plight and sypathetic to his cause--my own mother had recently been in the hospital--I took on his task and became "the helpful citizen," a title he himself gave me. As we departed--he to the station, I toward my office--I wondered how far the post office was as a panandler shifted in his sleep.

story.0: Growing up, we cultivate images of ourselves as we interact with the people around us.  These ideas of ourselves may be different from each other.  My biological father was selfish, greedy, stingy, and indifferent to myself and my mother for a very long tme, and yet he projects entirely different qualities onto me.  Seeing perhaps the best in himself reflected in his daughter who he barely knows.  Despite the sugary words he bandied about with me, his aloof and uncaring behavior spoke more.  In the reckonng that must come for all young adults, where I considered what was unfair in my life, why it was unfair, the good and the harm that I experienced, and what any of it meant for my relationships, I had to be disloyal to some of the images I had previously eld about myself and my family.  Those ideas had to be left behind for adult concepts of ambiguity.  I abandoned the idea I had of my father as a mean-spirited man and replaced it with a mysterious brokenness.  And yet it is my turn, perhaps, to be uncarig, because I have little compassion for him.

story.1:
Today was the big day: a department store nearby was having a big sale! Almost everything had its price slashed significantly. I'm not one for shopping, usually, but I'm also short on cash, so I didn't think it would hurt to check it out. At best, I couldsave some money; at worst, I'd lose nothing but a little bit of time. After a quick glance out the window to check the weather, I got dressed, grabbed my keys, and headed out of the house. The temperature was warm and it was sunny outside; a great day. I limbed into my car and sped off.

The drive wasn't short, but it wasn't long either - about thirty minutes. I didn't know what exactly I was looking for, so I perused some of the aisles, looking to see if there was anything interesting. I quickly found yself a bit disappointed; I'd been hoping for something practical or at least suited to my tastes, but there appeared to be nothing interesting. One aisle was for office supplies; the shelves were lined with staplers, scissors, and folders. Practical stuf, but I didn't need any of it. Another sold some electronics, but most of them were badly outdated; who still has a radio these days?! Finally, after twenty minutes and still not having found anything appealing or useful, I just grabbed a book off the shef so as to not have completely wasted my time, paid for it, and left. I'm definitely not one for shopping.
explain: My first reaction was to select 100%, but as cost is a factor, 60% seems to be an acceptable middle ground. Legislation did not factor into my decision so much as just being environmentally conscious.

I get onlineand do a few searches looking for some ideas to jar me loose. I end up at Amazon looking at a book that might provide some answers but I don't think it is worth the price. Other managers have a financial incentive to cheat by running their filters less than 60% of the time. I can try and keep the average at 60% by running my filters more than 60% of the time. At first this might seem like a good idea because running my filtrs 100% of the time is still 1 million dollars cheaper than the cost of legislation. However, it gives the cheaters, those running less than 60% of the time, an unfair advantage by having lower costs.

The only hope of ensuring a level playing field is f the filtering is mandated by legislation. By running my filters 0% of the time I will either force legislation, giving greater protection against cheating, or I will continue to reap the benefits of cheating.

story.1: Rachel sauntered into the house and flopped her keys and folder down on the table. It had been a harrowing day. The temperature had risen to well over 100f despite the forecast she overheard on the radio that morning. Her car, having seen it's best days, idn't like these temps and broke down on the way to class. So much for her plans to go shopping after class! She was relieved to be home at last. She took her Econ 101 book from her bag and sprawled out on her lounger near the window.

story.1: I was listening to Ernest Tubb on the radio in my car, holding my keys in my hand. Parked outside my house, I could see my wife through the window. In her hand, she held a folder as thick as a book, and from the look on her face, I could tell the temperatre was about to increase. "Maybe I should just go do the shopping," I thought -- but that would never do, and I dashed the thought from my mind. "Face the music" sang ol' Ernest, and I decided to brave the storm.
explain: Regardless of the bottom line, the social responsibility that is incumbent upon all people trumps any sort of profit-motive that might conspire to prevent me from using the filters. Perhaps even more ideally, my company could fund research that would innoate a way to produce my product without the byproduct. I would think that allocating the entirety of the profits for about three years would be appropriate to the task and would be an appropriate expenditure.
